					<outline text="WHO to hold emergency talks on deadly MERS virus Tuesday">
						<outline text="Link to Article" type="link" url="http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/world/who-to-hold-emergency/1100684.html"/>
						<outline text="Archived Version" type="link" url="http://adam.curry.com/art/1399740536_J6BM2Rqb.html"/>
						<outline text="Source: WT Newsfeed" type="link" url="http://cartusers.curry.com/w.trompYZn8/wtnewsfeed"/>
						<outline text="Sat, 10 May 2014 16:48"/>
						<outline text=""/>
						<outline text="GENEVA: The World Health Organization said Friday it would hold an emergency meeting next week on the deadly MERS virus, amid concern over the rising number of cases in several countries."/>
						<outline text="The UN health agency will host the emergency meeting on Tuesday to discuss the worrying spread of the virus, which in less than two years has killed 126 people in Saudi Arabia alone, spokesman Tarik Jasarevic told reporters in Geneva."/>
						<outline text="The WHO's emergency committee has already met four times to discuss the mysterious corona virus, which surfaced in mid-2012."/>
						<outline text="&quot;The increase in the number of cases in different countries raises a number of questions,&quot; Jasarevic said, without giving further details of the aim of the new talks."/>
						<outline text="The WHO experts will brief reporters at the end of the teleconferenced meeting on Tuesday evening, he said."/>
						<outline text="The Middle East Respiratory Syndrome coronavirus (MERS-CoV) is considered a deadlier but less-transmissible cousin of the SARS virus that broke out in Asia in 2003, infecting 8,273 people and killing nearly 800 of them."/>
						<outline text="Like SARS, it appears to cause a lung infection, with patients suffering from a temperature, coughing and breathing difficulties."/>
						<outline text="But it differs in that it also causes rapid kidney failure."/>
						<outline text="There are no vaccines or antiviral treatments for MERS, a disease that kills more than 40 per cent of those infected and that experts are still struggling to understand."/>
						<outline text="According to the most recent WHO figures, 496 MERS cases have been detected since September 2012."/>
						<outline text="The Saudi health ministry says 463 of them have been in the Gulf nation."/>
						<outline text="MERS cases have also been reported in the United Arab Emirates, Jordan, Egypt, Lebanon and even the United States, with most involving people who had travelled to Saudi Arabia or worked there, often as medical staff."/>
						</outline>
