					<outline text="VIDEO-DPRK-Amanpour">
						<outline text="Link to Article" type="link" url="http://amanpour.blogs.cnn.com/2014/05/08/defector-shadowy-organization-not-kim-jong-un-controls-north-korea/?hpt=hp_c1"/>
						<outline text="Archived Version" type="link" url="http://adam.curry.com/art/1399739922_WTJbauy6.html"/>
						<outline text="Sat, 10 May 2014 16:38"/>
						<outline text=""/>
						<outline text="By Mick Krever, CNN"/>
						<outline text="Who controls the Hermit Kingdom?"/>
						<outline text="According to a North Korean defector '' a former regime insider who was one of Kim Jong Il's favorite poet-propagandists '' it is not the 31-year-old dictator Kim Jong Un."/>
						<outline text="''When Kim Jong Il died and Kim Jong Un succeeded him, people saw the transfer of power from father to son,'' Jang Jin-Sung told CNN's Christiane Amanpour in London. ''What they did not see also was what happened to the apparatus of the totalitarian system that supported the rule of Kim Jong Il.''"/>
						<outline text="That apparatus, Jang said, is the Organization and Guidance Department, or OGD '' it was Kim Jong Il's education as he rose through the ranks, and was full of his university friends."/>
						<outline text="It is an ''old-boy's network'' made into a massive surveillance organization."/>
						<outline text="''Kim Jong Il had the OGD as his old boys' network,'' Jang told Amanpour. ''Kim Jong-un may have friends in his Swiss school, but he has no one inside North Korea.''"/>
						<outline text="Jang is the author of a new book, &quot;Dear Leader: Poet, Spy, Escapee '' A Look Inside North Korea.&quot;"/>
						<outline text="''After the execution of Jang Song Thaek [Kim Jong Un's uncle], he has become an orphan '' not just in terms of family connections, but in terms of politics.''"/>
						<outline text="''He's a political orphan.''"/>
						<outline text="Precious little is known about Kim Jong Un, who inherited the leadership of North Korea after his father's death in 2011."/>
						<outline text="Since that time, Jang said, Kim Jong Un has had to rely on his father's ''old-boys network'' to get anything done."/>
						<outline text="But because that group does not respect the younger Kim, who was educated in Switzerland, the way it did his father, Kim Jong Un has become nothing more than the symbolic head of North Korea."/>
						<outline text="Defector: I saw Kim Jong Il as 'divine'Meeting Kim"/>
						<outline text="''Until the day I met Kim Jong Il,'' Jang says, ''I truly considered him divine, as someone more holy, like a sage '' someone to be revered, someone who was better than us, who was sacrificing his own life for the people.''"/>
						<outline text="So effective was the regime propaganda machine, he told Amanpour, that he did not even believe that Kim the elder used the toilet."/>
						<outline text="But Jang, a poet, caught the dictator's eye, and was invited for a private audience with him."/>
						<outline text="''The man I saw standing in front of me was a man, he was a human being. He was not a holy man; he was not a saint; he was not a god. He was a man just like me, who did use the toilet.''"/>
						<outline text="In propaganda, Kim had used ''perfectly composed, flowery language,'' Jang said, and was deeply reverential of ''the people.''"/>
						<outline text="''But when I met him, he just spoke in slang like in a kind of commanding colloquial, working-class slang, even to his most senior men.''"/>
						<outline text="''And that was shocking to me.''"/>
						<outline text="He even, Jang told Amanpour, wore shoes to boost his height."/>
						<outline text="Defector lifts curtain on North KoreaShattering the myth"/>
						<outline text="Once a North Korean has been admitted into the dictator's inner circle, Jang said '' ''after having spent more than twenty minutes with him behind closed doors, at his personal request'' '' the leader's ''divinity'' gets transferred onto that person."/>
						<outline text="''You become immune from all prosecution, all harm. You're protected by his divinity.''"/>
						<outline text="From that highest perch of North Korean society, Jang could clearly see for the first time all the lies he had been told."/>
						<outline text="The truth became even starker when he went back to visit his hometown of Sairwon, in the southwest of the country."/>
						<outline text="''That was when I really witnessed the devastating effects of the famine. That's where I saw the corpses in the station area just piling up and being taken away.''"/>
						<outline text="As many as 3.5 million people are estimated to have died during North Korea's severe famine of the 1990s, according to the South Korean NGO Good Friends Center for Peace, Human Rights, and Refugees. (Official North Korean numbers estimate that 220,000 people died.)"/>
						<outline text="It is also, he told Amanpour, where he saw a public execution."/>
						<outline text="''It is not classified as a punishment in response to a crime. It's considered a method of moral education, of building up society's standards of morality. So that's why these executions happen in public places, such as market squares, where people watch it.''"/>
						<outline text="''It becomes a theater.''"/>
						<outline text="A decade ago Jang decided to flee the country. Not even his family knew he was planning to leave."/>
						<outline text="Had he told them, he told Amanpour, their innocence would have been compromised, and they would have been vulnerable to the wrath of the state security service."/>
						<outline text="Cracking the regime"/>
						<outline text="The most closed country on earth continues to fascinate the world, and among the most discussed questions is if, and how, the brutal regime could fall."/>
						<outline text="''Currently, there are two classes in North Korea locked in battle with each other,'' Jang said."/>
						<outline text="''One I will call the loyal class. This is the class that is invested, that has a stake in this continuation of the status quo, of oppression and surveillance and control.''"/>
						<outline text="''The other class are the market classes,'' he said. ''Their livelihoods are not sustained by the system, but actually oppressed by it.''"/>
						<outline text="Earlier this year, a PBS Frontline documentary featured stunning footage of ordinary North Koreans using free enterprise and challenging regime security officers."/>
						<outline text="North Koreans, the documentary showed, are increasingly exposed to the outside world, through smuggled DVDs and USB sticks containing Western and South Korean movies and TV shows."/>
						<outline text="''In the past, there was only one thing to belong to, one thing that sustained you, one thing that kept your family going'...loyalty to the cult of Kim.''"/>
						<outline text="''But now people have realized finally, after the famine, that it is not loyalty that feeds them. It is money. It is work. It is owning something. It's individual property that feeds one.''"/>
						<outline text="''So loyalty to Kim Il Sung'' '' Kim Jong Un's grandfather '' ''has been trumped by, let's say, the portrait of Washington on a U.S. dollar note.''"/>
						<outline text="Change in North Korea will not come, Jang said, by negotiating with the regime. It will come through knowledge."/>
						<outline text="''Truth will set North Korea free. The people will set North Korea free. The erosion of control will set North Korea free, not engagement with the regime.''"/>
						</outline>
